Description: A masterfully rendered oil depiction of key players in the conflict between the Garlean Empire and its erstwhile territories Ala Mhigo and Doma. The sense of impending liberation is authentic indeed.
Name: Authentic Copy of Liberation

Singular: authentic copy of The Legend Returns
Plural: authentic copies of The Legend Returns
Description: A masterfully rendered oil depiction of figures from Ivalician legend old and new. The pervading orangey-brownness of the piece gives it a palpable sense of authenticity.
Name: Authentic Copy of The Legend Returns

Singular: authentic copy of Rise of a New Sun
Plural: authentic copies of Rise of a New Sun
Description: A masterfully rendered oil depiction of certain employees of Garlond Ironworks and an enigmatic piece of technology. The most authentic element of this piece is undoubtedly the depiction of a bulbous-headed yellow birdlike thing.
Name: Authentic Copy of Rise of a New Sun

Singular: authentic copy of Under the Moonlight
Plural: authentic copies of Under the Moonlight
Description: A masterfully rendered oil depiction of the erstwhile acting imperial viceroy of Doma, Yotsuyu, and those instrumental in her destruction. The depiction of these pivotal figures under the moonlight, the serious moonlight, is unmistakably authentic.
Name: Authentic Copy of Under the Moonlight

Singular: authentic copy of Prelude in Violet
Plural: authentic copies of Prelude in Violet
Description: A masterfully rendered oil depiction of the ruthless Garlean elite and a few noble souls who sought to stop their nefarious machinations. Some have remarked that Gaius Baelsar appears to be somewhat under the weather in this piece, but those who have been in contact with the man maintain that it is an entirely authentic depiction.
Name: Authentic Copy of Prelude in Violet

Singular: authentic copy of Requiem for Heroes
Plural: authentic copies of Requiem for Heroes
Description: A masterfully rendered oil depiction of a noble warrior who journeyed across many a realm to fight for the sake of the common man. The flag-to-man ratio lends it a certain air of authenticity, and evokes images of a samurai rampaging through a textiles store.
Name: Authentic Copy of Requiem for Heroes

Description: Someday your prince (or princess) will come. Probably not in this, though. The smell, however, is said to authentically resemble that of real pumpkins, though this is seldom considered a priority by potential passengers.
Name: Authentic Pumpkin Carriage

Singular: authentic fantastical All Saints' Wake advertisement
Plural: authentic fantastical All Saints' Wake advertisements
Description: A hand-painted notice advertising the All Saints' Wake festivities of yesteryear. Authentic down to the last brushstroke? Absolutely. Nightmare-inducing and spine-tinglingly terrifying? Not so much.
Name: Authentic Fantastical All Saints' Wake Advertisement

Description: Perfected Skysteel tool.
Name: Skybuilders' Saw

Description: Perfected Skysteel tool.
Name: Skybuilders' Cross-pein Hammer

Description: Perfected Skysteel tool.
Name: Skybuilders' Raising Hammer

Description: Perfected Skysteel tool.
Name: Skybuilders' Lapidary Hammer

Description: Perfected Skysteel tool.
Name: Skybuilders' Round Knife

Description: Perfected Skysteel tool.
Name: Skybuilders' Needle

Description: Perfected Skysteel tool.
Name: Skybuilders' Alembic

Description: Perfected Skysteel tool.
Name: Skybuilders' Frypan

Description: Perfected Skysteel tool.
Name: Skybuilders' Hatchet

Description: Perfected Skysteel tool.
Name: Skybuilders' Pickaxe

Description: Perfected Skysteel tool.
Name: Skybuilders' Fishing Rod

Description: The words “delicate” and “saw” are seldom seen in such close proximity.
Name: Oddly Delicate Saw Part

Description: Presumably once this delicate part is attached to the rest of the tool, it will somehow gain the ability to withstand all the hammering that is sure to follow.
Name: Oddly Delicate Cross-pein Hammer Part

Description: Thankfully the pot used to house the part and the protective jelly in which it is suspended are considerably less delicate. Obviously shaking or dropping it would be extremely ill-advised.
Name: Oddly Delicate Raising Hammer Part

Description: A small round pot may not seem the obvious choice for the transportation of parts of any kind, regardless of their delicate nature, but perhaps the Skysteel engineers had a surplus of them lying about the manufactory.
Name: Oddly Delicate Lapidary Hammer Part

Description: Some of the Skysteel engineers fear that due to its delicate nature, this particular part may struggle to fit in with the rather more robust components that comprise the round knife.
Name: Oddly Delicate Round Knife Part

Description: Needles, by and large, tend not to include multiple parts, but the Skysteel engineers have ever sought to defy common sense.
Name: Oddly Delicate Needle Part

Description: Even a standard alembic is rather fragile to begin with, so adding an oddly delicate part will only exacerbate the problem.
Name: Oddly Delicate Alembic Part

Description: One can only hope that the liberal application of heat does not offend this part's delicate sensibilities.
Name: Oddly Delicate Frypan Part

Description: Once the hatchet is completed, one must remember to go about their hacking and slashing with great care so as not to spoil the oddly delicate part attached to it.
Name: Oddly Delicate Hatchet Part

Description: It would probably be sensible to protect this inconceivably delicate part with rather less delicate parts.
Name: Inconceivably Delicate Hatchet Part

Description: Time will tell whether the addition of this oddly delicate part will actually improve one's ability to smash rocks into smaller rocks.
Name: Oddly Delicate Pickaxe Part

Description: Poor workmen who blame their tools will have no excuses once this piece is attached.
Name: Inconceivably Delicate Pickaxe Part

Description: Your fellow anglers will no doubt be impressed by the length to which you have gone to improve your fishing rod. After all, showing off in front of others is what fishing is all about.
Name: Oddly Delicate Fishing Rod Part

Description: Only the most dedicated of fishers would even consider the use of such an oddly delicate component, but the obsessive pursuit of the very best equipment available is as much a part of the hobby as actually catching the fish.
Name: Oddly Delicate Fishing Reel Part

Singular: length of oddly delicate pine lumber
Plural: lengths of oddly delicate pine lumber
Description: Though it may seem as sturdy as any other length of lumber, it will be robbed of its intrinsic qualities if one so much as sneezes near it.
Name: Oddly Delicate Pine Lumber

Description: Perhaps it would be prudent to match this gear with others of a similarly delicate disposition.
Name: Oddly Delicate Silver Gear

Description: This delicate square must be treated with the utmost care before holding it over a blazing forge and smashing it repeatedly with a hammer.
Name: Oddly Delicate Wolfram Square

Description: The rays of light refracted by this crystal are so delicate that they can be broken simply by waving one's hand through them.
Name: Oddly Delicate Celestine

Singular: circle of oddly delicate gazelle leather
Plural: circles of oddly delicate gazelle leather
Description: This leather somehow managed to retain its delicacy despite being subjected to the far-from-gentle tanning process.
Name: Oddly Delicate Gazelle Leather

Singular: bolt of oddly delicate rhea cloth
Plural: bolts of oddly delicate rhea cloth
Description: Great care must be taken not to stretch, crumple, crease, or─if possible─touch this specimen, lest its intrinsic delicateness be marred.
Name: Oddly Delicate Rhea Cloth

Singular: bottle of oddly delicate holy water
Plural: bottles of oddly delicate holy water
Description: Most water is delicate by its very nature, this sort even more so.
Name: Oddly Delicate Holy Water

Singular: bottle of oddly delicate shark oil
Plural: bottles of oddly delicate shark oil
Description: The treatment to which the shark was subjected to extract its oil was anything but delicate.
Name: Oddly Delicate Shark Oil

Description: Yes, this is a delicate log. Oddly so, in fact.
Name: Oddly Delicate Pine Log

Singular: chunk of oddly delicate silvergrace ore
Plural: chunks of oddly delicate silvergrace ore
Description: For all its delicacy, this is nevertheless a chunk of ore, and quite capable of leaving a nasty mark when thrown at someone's head.
Name: Oddly Delicate Silvergrace Ore

Description: While standard scheelite is certainly rare, the oddly delicate variant is scarce to the point of being practically nonexistent.
Name: Oddly Delicate Scheelite

Description: This chunk of unrefined crystal is not itself especially delicate, but has the potential to produce pieces of remarkable delicacy. Whether this is beneficial in any way whatsoever, however, remains to be seen.
Name: Oddly Delicate Raw Celestine

Description: Rest assured that the gazelle to which this once belonged was slaughtered in the most delicate way possible.
Name: Oddly Delicate Gazelle Hide

Description: Rhea this oddly delicate is reserved for the production of oddly delicate rhea cloth. It is then, in turn, used to make all sorts of cloth-based items, provided that they are not hindered in any way by being oddly delicate, which rules out practically everything.
Name: Oddly Delicate Rhea

Description: If one happens to eat one of these poisonous berries, they may find that their stomach also becomes oddly delicate.
Name: Oddly Delicate Mistletoe

Description: The “oddly delicate” part refers not to the shark's physical attributes, but to its demeanor. Due to being dead, however, this is something of a moot point.
Name: Oddly Delicate Hammerhead Shark

Description: For all the feathers adorning a cloudkin's body, only a rare few could be considered oddly delicate. Those are generally found around the wingpit, the avian equivalent of an armpit, obviously.
Name: Oddly Delicate Feather

Description: Oddly delicate for a birch log, though still fairly hefty by most people's standards.
Name: Oddly Delicate Birch Log

Singular: chunk of oddly delicate adamantite ore
Plural: chunks of oddly delicate adamantite ore
Description: Adamantite, as the name would suggest, is anything but delicate, though this particular sample is perhaps ever-so-slightly less than “practically indestructible.”
Name: Oddly Delicate Adamantite Ore

Singular: piece of oddly delicate raw jade
Plural: pieces of oddly delicate raw jade
Description: Hopefully not so delicate that it will shatter into a thousand pieces at the first attempt to refine it.
Name: Oddly Delicate Raw Jade

Description:
The glow it emits when swimming through the ocean depths is reminiscent of sparks flying from a struck flint. Thankfully, it does not present an actual fire hazard, despite what some may think.

Can only be caught when equipped with a skysung fishing rod.

[Suitable for printing on medium canvases.]
Name: Flintstrike

Description:
Closely resembling a moogle's pom-pom, apart from the strange odor. Saying it smells pickled is a rather charitable description.

Can only be caught when equipped with a skysung fishing rod.

[Suitable for printing on small canvases.]
Name: Pickled Pom

This diluted brew temporarily increases strength for twice the duration of similar potions.

Duration: 30s
Name: Grade 4 Tincture of Strength

Description:
This diluted brew temporarily increases dexterity for twice the duration of similar potions.

Duration: 30s
Name: Grade 4 Tincture of Dexterity

Description:
This diluted brew temporarily increases vitality for twice the duration of similar potions.

Duration: 30s
Name: Grade 4 Tincture of Vitality

Description:
This diluted brew temporarily increases intelligence for twice the duration of similar potions.

Duration: 30s

Description:
This diluted brew temporarily increases mind for twice the duration of similar potions.

Duration: 30s

Description:
A simple-but-satisfying dish of thinly worked dough topped with tomatoes and cheese, baked in a wood-fired oven until crispy. 

EXP Bonus: +3% Duration: 30m
(Duration can be extended to 60m by consuming multiple servings)
Name: Pizza

Description:
Using choice ingredients such as mist spinach and mozzarella, this variation of spinach quiche satisfies even the fussiest gourmand.

EXP Bonus: +3% Duration: 30m
(Duration can be extended to 60m by consuming multiple servings)
Name: Mist Spinach Quiche

Description:
Flat, thick pasta smothered in a rich cream sauce with tender slices of chicken thigh.

EXP Bonus: +3% Duration: 30m
(Duration can be extended to 60m by consuming multiple servings)
Name: Chicken Fettuccine

Description:
A leg of chicken patiently smoked to perfection.

EXP Bonus: +3% Duration: 30m
(Duration can be extended to 60m by consuming multiple servings)
Name: Smoked Chicken

Description:
Tart and invigorating juice freshly squeezed from golden pineapples.

EXP Bonus: +3% Duration: 30m
(Duration can be extended to 60m by consuming multiple servings)
Name: Golden Pineapple Juice

Description:
A salad featuring chunks of golden pineapple tossed with a flavorsome frantoio oil dressing.

EXP Bonus: +3% Duration: 30m
(Duration can be extended to 60m by consuming multiple servings)
Name: Pineapple Salad

Description:
An irresistibly soft and airy confectionary made from whipped twilight apple purée.

EXP Bonus: +3% Duration: 30m
(Duration can be extended to 60m by consuming multiple servings)
Name: Zefir

Description:
Shredded twilight apples give this popoto salad a crunchy texture and fruity tang.

EXP Bonus: +3% Duration: 30m
(Duration can be extended to 60m by consuming multiple servings)
Name: Twilight Popoto Salad

Description:
Broad beans stewed with fragrant spices, served with a side of steamed rice.

EXP Bonus: +3% Duration: 30m
(Duration can be extended to 60m by consuming multiple servings)
Name: Broad Bean Curry

Description:
A sweet and zesty muffin made by mixing lemonette rind and juice into the dough.

EXP Bonus: +3% Duration: 30m
(Duration can be extended to 60m by consuming multiple servings)
Name: Lemon Muffin

Description: A fresh, springy cheese made from buffalo milk.
Name: Mozzarella

Description: The thigh of a breed of chicken known for the superior flavor and texture of its flesh.
Name: Chicken Thigh

Description: A golden-hued variety of pineapple touted for its tart flavor.
Name: Golden Pineapple

Description: A sweet-sour variety of apple named for the gentle gleam of its peel.
Name: Twilight Apple

Description: Boasting a unique fragrance, these seeds are the secret spice in myriad recipes.
Name: Cardamom

Description: The skybuilders are known for plying their trade by applying plies to provide supplies of plywood. Now try saying that ten times fast with a mouthful of porridge.
Name: Grade 4 Skybuilders' Plywood

Description: A marvelous mixture of malleable metals melded into magnificently molded...blocks.
Name: Grade 4 Skybuilders' Alloy

Description: To be fair is rare, and to be square even rarer, but to be both fair and square is miraculous indeed.
Name: Grade 4 Skybuilders' Steel Plate

Description: It is believed in certain circles that the word “ingot” is derived from the verb “to inget” meaning “to breathe in and out simultaneously, causing the air to become trapped in the larynx, creating a sound akin to a hiccupping buffalo.”
Name: Grade 4 Skybuilders' Ingot

Description: The time and effort spent on cutting each hide into perfect circles would have been better spent on...well, anything else. Not to mention the amount of wasted leather now lying in a pile of offcuts. However, one thing can be said of the skybuilders: there is madness in their method.
Name: Grade 4 Skybuilders' Leather

Description: While this may seem like a good choice for a children's skipping rope, it is weighty enough to leave a painful welt on either the temples or ankles of those with a poor sense of timing. Still, some might say that only adds to the fun.
Name: Grade 4 Skybuilders' Rope

Description: The grade 4 variety of ink is said to be especially quick-drying, which helps to prevent smudging. Some claim, however, that the ink dries before it even has time to reach the parchment, which does rather defeat the purpose of the ink in the first place.
Name: Grade 4 Skybuilders' Ink

Singular: bottle of grade 4 skybuilders' hemp milk
Plural: bottles of grade 4 skybuilders' hemp milk
Description:
“We challenged Ishgardians to taste the difference between hemp milk and a leading dairy-based competitor. Eight in ten participants claimed they tasted exactly the same, while the remainder complained of a stomachache from drinking too much milk.”
─Culinarians' Guild researcher
Name: Grade 4 Skybuilders' Hemp Milk

Description:
“If you see a crate, try looking inside. There may be a small amount of gil or even potions or medicinal herbs inside. Don't worry about the owners catching you pilfering their wares; you'd be surprised how many are willing to turn a blind eye, especially if you're carrying a big sword.”
─Adventuring for Fun and Profit, First Edition
Name: Grade 4 Skybuilders' Crate

Description: In traditional Doman carpentry, the wooden pieces are carefully carved to allow them to snugly interlock and remain steadfast for years to come. In Ishgard, however, the wood is considerably less cooperative, and must have little metal spikes driven through it to stay where it is told.
Name: Grade 4 Skybuilders' Nails

Description: Although being covered in rivets tends to make basically anything look a lot more sturdy, the act of driving them in to begin with probably compromises the object's structural integrity to some degree. It certainly has that effect on a person's skull.
Name: Grade 4 Skybuilders' Rivets

Description: Those who cannot afford proper metal gauntlets can try threading these metallic rings onto their fingers to produce a similar effect. Just be sure to keep your fists clenched to stop them falling off.
Name: Grade 4 Skybuilders' Rings

Singular: bundle of grade 4 skybuilders' leather straps
Plural: bundles of grade 4 skybuilders' leather straps
Description: The artisans responsible for the creation of such wares are often described as “strapping,” but usually in a literal rather than figurative sense.
Name: Grade 4 Skybuilders' Leather Straps

Description: How long is a bolt of cloth? Twice as long from the middle to the end.
Name: Grade 4 Skybuilders' Cloth

Singular: phial of grade 4 skybuilders' plant oil
Plural: phials of grade 4 skybuilders' plant oil
Description: Best burned at midnight.
Name: Grade 4 Skybuilders' Plant Oil

Description: Ishgardian parents often tell their children that the sesame seeds are in fact dead flies that were trapped in the batter prior to baking. Not only does this have the effect of keeping the young ones' hands out of the cookie jar, it also leads them to a few raised eyebrows in regard to their parents' choice of confectionery.
Name: Grade 4 Skybuilders' Sesame Cookie

Description: One of the few wheels that can turn all day and not move an ilm.
Name: Grade 4 Skybuilders' Spinning Wheel

Description: A common choice of weapon in civilian uprisings, though it leaves much to be desired in the “long and pointy” stakes, unlike the ever-popular pitchfork.
Name: Grade 4 Skybuilders' Hatchet

Description: Almost identical to the grade 3 version but with a better warranty, providing cover against “irremovable stains except for in cases where strange or unusual ingredients have been used, such as Lalafell fat.”
Name: Grade 4 Skybuilders' Cookpot

Description: A frame so intricately detailed and immaculately crafted that it threatens to upstage the embroidery it is designed to keep in place.
Name: Grade 4 Skybuilders' Embroidery Frame

Description: The leather of this sack once held the flesh, bones, and organs of a large beast, but has now been granted the opportunity to store a much wider and more interesting range of objects. Unless, that is, it is purchased by a butcher, in which case the contents may end up being largely the same as its previous incarnation.
Name: Grade 4 Skybuilders' Leather Sack

Description: Combatants who claim they will “sweep the floor” with their opponent should try one of these brooms instead. Twice the cleanliness with none of the violence.
Name: Grade 4 Skybuilders' Broom

Singular: bottle of grade 4 skybuilders' holy water
Plural: bottles of grade 4 skybuilders' holy water
Description:
“Why's this called holy water? I don't see any holes in it.”
─A confused and somewhat illiterate skybuilder
Name: Grade 4 Skybuilders' Holy Water

Description: Contains so much sugar that some claim the smell alone is enough to make one's teeth fall out.
Name: Grade 4 Skybuilders' Tea

Description: “Takes just as many steps to climb up as it does to climb down” is the slogan used by the skybuilders when pitching their stepladders to potential customers, though any sales made tend to be in spite of said slogan rather than because of it.
Name: Grade 4 Skybuilders' Stepladder

Description: Strangely enough, it is not particularly well suited to cutting crosses.
Name: Grade 4 Skybuilders' Crosscut Saw

Description: As any smith will attest, the heat of the forge can be overwhelming. Were it not for the conveniently placed air holes, their heads would be baked inside their mesails like cow-brain pies (an Ishgardian delicacy).
Name: Grade 4 Skybuilders' Mesail

Description: Since ancient times, man has sought to move exceedingly large blocks of stone from one location to another. In the past, methods such as conveying the material atop a series of rolling logs or ferrying it on extremely buoyant rafts were employed, whereas all it requires these days is one plucky volunteer with bottomless pockets.
Name: Grade 4 Skybuilders' Stone

Description: It is said that over the years, the design for longboots grew longer and longer, until the two boots eventually met in the middle and lost the part covering the foot entirely─perhaps to save on materials─and became what are now known as trousers.
Name: Grade 4 Skybuilders' Longboots

Description: Long have gloves waged war in the marketplace against mittens, their archrivals, though the wearer's ability to move each finger individually has proved to be a deciding factor in securing their popularity.
Name: Grade 4 Skybuilders' Gloves

Description: In a stroke of sheer genius, the skybuilders have succeeded in inventing a variety of soap that floats on water, much to the delight of the people of Ishgard─those who actually wash, that is.
Name: Grade 4 Skybuilders' Soap

Description: A remarkable concoction that is able to treat any ailment the salesperson is able to imagine. The lack of complaints following purchase indicates that the customer is either entirely satisfied with the effects, or dead from poisoning.
Name: Grade 4 Skybuilders' All-purpose Infusion

Description: The mattress is made from a spongelike material to help absorb any...nocturnal spillages.
Name: Grade 4 Skybuilders' Bed

Description: Sometimes, the phrase “she's got a bun in the oven” is meant to be taken literally. In fact, this common saying has led to all sorts of hilarious misunderstandings, particularly in cases where the woman in question likes to bake her own bread.
Name: Grade 4 Skybuilders' Oven

Description: Spare a thought for the poor souls whose job it is to light each of the lanterns that line the streets of the Firmament every evening. Perhaps one day, someone will be so kind as to invent a system whereby they may be lit and extinguished remotely. Unfortunately, many of Ishgard's civic engineers are preoccupied with far more frivolous pursuits, such as imbuing tools with mystic energy using oddly specific materials.
Name: Grade 4 Skybuilders' Lamppost

Description: One must take great care not to confuse this with the similarly named ladies' undergarment.
Name: Grade 4 Skybuilders' Brazier

Description: While it is common for mud, paint, and other stains to collect on overalls, some of the skybuilders have taken to deliberately dirtying their clothing to fool others into thinking they have been hard at work. Since a skybuilder's pay is largely based on their performance, however, those who attempt such tricks are normally left with naught but soiled overalls and empty pockets.
Name: Grade 4 Skybuilders' Overalls

Description: Is there anything more pleasant than yawning in the morning as day is dawning, beneath an awning?
Name: Grade 4 Skybuilders' Awning

Singular: bottle of grade 4 skybuilders' growth formula
Plural: bottles of grade 4 skybuilders' growth formula
Description: There are rumors that claim the remarkable height of Elezen is due to doses of growth formula being slipped into their morning porridge from a young age. Attempts to reproduce such an effect on the Lalafells who willingly volunteered as test subjects have yet to yield results, other than an unnatural aversion to porridge.
Name: Grade 4 Skybuilders' Growth Formula

Description: Many culinarians believe the secret to a good stew is to never allow the pot to become empty by constantly topping it up with fresh ingredients. This may in fact be an elaborate ploy to avoid ever having to wash the pot, not to mention that some parts of the stew may have been in the mix for several years without being served. Diners are advised to “eat around” anything that seems a bit suspicious.
Name: Grade 4 Skybuilders' Stew

Description: Though such a device would seem to have little use in Ishgard, where foodstuffs may be kept chilled simply by placing them outside, the icebox does offer protection from rats and crows. But then again, so would any other type of box.
Name: Grade 4 Artisanal Skybuilders' Icebox

Description: If it starts spinning wildly, it means the wind is blowing in all of the directions at once.
Name: Grade 4 Artisanal Skybuilders' Chocobo Weathervane

Description: This communal deposit relies on the honesty of not only every member of the company─to give what they can and take only what they need─but every other person who passes through the Firmament, as it is left completely unlocked at all times. The members of said companies are often surprised to find the chest completely empty upon opening it, while opportunistic thieves enjoy their easy pickings.
Name: Grade 4 Artisanal Skybuilders' Company Chest

Description: Such devices are often found pointing in the direction of the open-air baths, which is in keeping with the letter─rather than the spirit─of its intended purpose, that being “the observation of heavenly bodies.”
Name: Grade 4 Artisanal Skybuilders' Astroscope

Description: While it may not seem especially voluminous, this belt is capable of holding up to thirty-five primary tools and the same number of secondary tools. One might have trouble actually moving with an entire shed's worth of heavy equipment hanging from one's waist, however.
Name: Grade 4 Artisanal Skybuilders' Tool Belt

Description: Far more luxurious than most other garments of its kind, with a price to match. Most would think twice before investing in this vest.
Name: Grade 4 Artisanal Skybuilders' Vest

Description:
“Should you find any mysterious phials of liquid, be sure to take them with you. After all, the clinking of glass from all the potions, ethers, and elixirs an adventurer is known for carrying about their person is one of the easiest ways for a potential client to distinguish them from a marauding barbarian.”
─Adventuring for Fun and Profit, First Edition
Name: Grade 4 Artisanal Skybuilders' Tincture

Singular: cup of grade 4 artisanal skybuilders' sorbet
Plural: cups of grade 4 artisanal skybuilders' sorbet
Description: Although a lot of care and effort went into the preparation of this sweet treat, a similar effect could easily be achieved by leaving a glass of fruit juice outside in the cold Ishgardian air for half a bell or so.
Name: Grade 4 Artisanal Skybuilders' Sorbet

Description:
As many Ishgardian schoolchildren will attest, telling one's detractors “Sticks and stones may break my bones, but words shall never harm me” is an open invitation to be assaulted with said objects.

Used in level 20 crafting recipes.
Name: Approved Grade 4 Skybuilders' Switch

Singular: tuft of approved grade 4 skybuilders' hemp
Plural: tufts of approved grade 4 skybuilders' hemp
Description:
Since time immemorial, this robust plant has helped many a convicted criminal dance the hempen jig.

Used in level 20 crafting recipes.
Name: Approved Grade 4 Skybuilders' Hemp

Singular: chunk of approved grade 4 skybuilders' iron ore
Plural: chunks of approved grade 4 skybuilders' iron ore
Description:
Any smith worth their salt will have a vast amount of ores, ingots, rivets, rings, and plates at their disposal, although finding space to store it all can prove most bothersome. Some have even taken to employing retainers for the sole purpose of lugging their surplus junk around.

Used in level 20 crafting recipes.
Name: Approved Grade 4 Skybuilders' Iron Ore

Singular: pinch of approved grade 4 skybuilders' iron sand
Plural: pinches of approved grade 4 skybuilders' iron sand
Description:
Primarily used as a vital component in a children's toy whereby hair and a beard may be applied to a picture of a man's face by means of an ingenious magnetic wand. (For ages three and up.)

Used in level 20 crafting recipes.
Name: Approved Grade 4 Skybuilders' Iron Sand

Description:
Used in the construction of various musical instruments and believed to imbue the music with a certain ethereal quality. This may or may not be due to the souls of elementals trapped within the wood, which brings a whole new meaning to the phrase “haunting melody.”

Used in level 40 crafting recipes.
Name: Approved Grade 4 Skybuilders' Mahogany Log

Singular: tuft of approved grade 4 skybuilders' sesame
Plural: tufts of approved grade 4 skybuilders' sesame
Description:
The sesame plant is robust enough to grow in even the most inhospitable environments, including those in which the botanists tasked with gathering said plant are incapable of surviving. As valuable as sesame is, most would agree it is not worth risking life and limb for, not that the skybuilders seem particularly bothered by this when making their requests...

Used in level 40 crafting recipes.
Name: Approved Grade 4 Skybuilders' Sesame

Description:
A freshly picked cotton boll with the stem still attached is the perfect implement for cleaning one's ears, though it is likely that the skybuilders will notice if that same cotton boll is submitted to them after being used. They tend to object to that sort of thing.

Used in level 40 crafting recipes.
Name: Approved Grade 4 Skybuilders' Cotton Boll

Singular: chunk of approved grade 4 skybuilders' ore
Plural: chunks of approved grade 4 skybuilders' ore
Description:
Only a true skybuilder could look at a nondescript lump of grey, slightly metallic rock and say, “Yes, this is definitely grade 4 skybuilders' ore,” though it could be argued that this is because they are the ones who named it to begin with.

Used in level 40 crafting recipes.
Name: Approved Grade 4 Skybuilders' Ore

Singular: chunk of approved grade 4 skybuilders' rock salt
Plural: chunks of approved grade 4 skybuilders' rock salt
Description:
“But Mother, can we not break the salt rock into smaller chunks to save us all from having to lick the same piece? It seems awfully unhygienic.”
“No, my sweet prince, that would not be proper. Now lick the rock and put it back on the table.”
─Typical Ishgardian mealtime conversation

Used in level 40 crafting recipes.
Name: Approved Grade 4 Skybuilders' Rock Salt

Singular: pinch of approved grade 4 skybuilders' mythrite sand
Plural: pinches of approved grade 4 skybuilders' mythrite sand
Description:
A popular choice for hourglasses as the speed at which the sand falls is directly affected by how much those in close proximity are enjoying themselves. With a mythrite sand hourglass, time really does fly when one is having fun.

Used in level 40 crafting recipes.
Name: Approved Grade 4 Skybuilders' Mythrite Sand

Description:
Spruce is the wood of choice in all manner of carpentry projects, from enormous load-bearing beams to tiny intricately carved ornaments. So versatile is it that one wonders why the skybuilders even bother with the other types of timber.

Used in level 60 and 70 crafting recipes.
Name: Approved Grade 4 Skybuilders' Spruce Log

Singular: sprig of approved grade 4 skybuilders' mistletoe
Plural: sprigs of approved grade 4 skybuilders' mistletoe
Description:
A prominent feature in many Starlight Celebration decorations, mistletoe is much loved by the people of Ishgard. Most people would probably view it rather differently, however, if they knew that the plant is in fact a voracious parasite that mercilessly drains the life from its host.

Used in level 60 and 70 crafting recipes.
Name: Approved Grade 4 Skybuilders' Mistletoe

Description:
You had best treat this warty little creature kindly as it may be a ninja's hellfrog in disguise. “Burned to death by flaming frog vomit” is hardly the sort of remark one wants in their obituary.

Used in level 60 and 70 crafting recipes.
Name: Approved Grade 4 Skybuilders' Toad

Description:
Although such vines make perfectly adequate replacements for rope, it seems that the skybuilders have more than enough actual rope to make the use of this plant somewhat redundant.

Used in level 60 and 70 crafting recipes.
Name: Approved Grade 4 Skybuilders' Vine

Singular: basket of approved grade 4 skybuilders' tea leaves
Plural: baskets of approved grade 4 skybuilders' tea leaves
Description:
“There are few problems that cannot be resolved─or at least, forgotten about─over a nice cup of tea.”
─Ishgardian aphorism

Used in level 60 and 70 crafting recipes.
Name: Approved Grade 4 Skybuilders' Tea Leaves

Singular: chunk of approved grade 4 skybuilders' electrum ore
Plural: chunks of approved grade 4 skybuilders' electrum ore
Description:
A naturally occurring alloy of gold and silver, though many would argue that it is worth less than the sum of its parts. Those expecting it to possess some sort of lightning-aspected aetherial properties due to the name are sure to be disappointed, although that has not prevented several unscrupulous merchants from advertising it as such.

Used in level 60 and 70 crafting recipes.
Name: Approved Grade 4 Skybuilders' Electrum Ore

Singular: pinch of approved grade 4 skybuilders' alumen
Plural: pinches of approved grade 4 skybuilders' alumen
Description:
Another in a seemingly endless list of powdered substances that are of vital importance to alchemists, goldsmiths, and the like, but mean─to quote the common vernacular─bugger all to everyone else. Luckily, laymen need only know how much it will fetch at market and whether or not one must face any life-endangering peril to obtain it.

Used in level 60 and 70 crafting recipes.
Name: Approved Grade 4 Skybuilders' Alumen

Singular: bottle of approved grade 4 skybuilders' spring water
Plural: bottles of approved grade 4 skybuilders' spring water
Description:
A number of stringent tests are performed to determine the grade assigned to spring water, including the measurement of time taken to evaporate when poured into a shallow dish and placed next to a hot pig.

Used in level 60 and 70 crafting recipes.
Name: Approved Grade 4 Skybuilders' Spring Water

Singular: pinch of approved grade 4 skybuilders' gold sand
Plural: pinches of approved grade 4 skybuilders' gold sand
Description:
Each grain of gold sand was once a whole nugget that has been gradually eroded over many thousands of years, which is a rather extreme example of depreciating value.

Used in level 60 and 70 crafting recipes.
Name: Approved Grade 4 Skybuilders' Gold Sand

Singular: slab of approved grade 4 skybuilders' ragstone
Plural: slabs of approved grade 4 skybuilders' ragstone
Description:
Due to being formed from compressed layers of sediment, ragstone may contain rare and precious fossils. The skybuilders, however, care not a jot about any of that and will happily use it to whet their blades and so forth, much to the woe of naturalists throughout Eorzea.

Used in level 60 and 70 crafting recipes.
Name: Approved Grade 4 Skybuilders' Ragstone

Singular: approved grade 4 skybuilders' white cedar log
Plural: approved grade 4 skybuilders' white cedar logs
Description:
White cedar is known to be one of the most longevous species of tree, with one particular specimen estimated to be 1,852 years old, according to the number of growth rings. Of course, it probably would have lived a lot longer if not for a glory-seeking, axe-happy botanist.

Used in level 80 crafting recipes.
Name: Approved Grade 4 Skybuilders' White Cedar Log

Singular: lump of approved grade 4 skybuilders' primordial resin
Plural: lumps of approved grade 4 skybuilders' primordial resin
Description:
Made from congealed primordial soup.

Used in level 80 crafting recipes.
Name: Approved Grade 4 Skybuilders' Primordial Resin

Singular: sheaf of approved grade 4 skybuilders' wheat
Plural: sheaves of approved grade 4 skybuilders' wheat
Description:
Ishgardian bakers organize a gathering known as a “wheat and greet,” in which they discuss a range of topics, such as the perfect method for wafting the smell of freshly baked bread into the streets to maximize profits.

Used in level 80 crafting recipes.
Name: Approved Grade 4 Skybuilders' Wheat

Singular: approved grade 4 skybuilders' gossamer cotton boll
Plural: approved grade 4 skybuilders' gossamer cotton bolls
Description:
When it comes to cotton bolls, this is the sovereign of softness, the commandant of comfort, the liege lord of loveliness.

Used in level 80 crafting recipes.
Name: Approved Grade 4 Skybuilders' Gossamer Cotton Boll

Description:
Those who believe dogs are man's best friend have obviously never met a tortoise.

Used in level 80 crafting recipes.
Name: Approved Grade 4 Skybuilders' Tortoise

Singular: chunk of approved grade 4 skybuilders' gold ore
Plural: chunks of approved grade 4 skybuilders' gold ore
Description:
“The ambassador's receptions are noted in society for their host's exquisite taste that captivates his guests. The tray of gold nuggets his butlers pass around, however, often leads to confusion and broken teeth when said guests mistake them for chocolate treats.”
─The Highs and Lows of Ishgardian High Society

Used in level 80 crafting recipes.
Name: Approved Grade 4 Skybuilders' Gold Ore

Singular: chunk of approved grade 4 skybuilders' finest rock salt
Plural: chunks of approved grade 4 skybuilders' finest rock salt
Description:
This particular variety of rock salt has proved so popular with Ishgardian diners, that many choose to forgo their meal altogether and spend the evening licking the communal salt rock instead.

Used in level 80 crafting recipes.
Name: Approved Grade 4 Skybuilders' Finest Rock Salt

Singular: bottle of approved grade 4 skybuilders' truespring water
Plural: bottles of approved grade 4 skybuilders' truespring water
Description:
The advertising slogan, “Spring water never tasted so true,” has left many Ishgardians both impressed and baffled in equal measure. Merchants are hopeful that this will cause just the right amount of confusion to distract from the fact it is essentially identical to the grade 3 variety. And any other type of water, for that matter.

Used in level 80 crafting recipes.
Name: Approved Grade 4 Skybuilders' Truespring Water

Singular: pinch of approved grade 4 skybuilders' mineral sand
Plural: pinches of approved grade 4 skybuilders' mineral sand
Description:
When the skybuilders were quizzed as to exactly what type of mineral comprises this sand, the reply was, “That information is on a need-to-know basis.” One would assume that those mining the stuff would need to know what they are supposed to be looking for, but the skybuilders move─and think─in mysterious ways.

Used in level 80 crafting recipes.
Name: Approved Grade 4 Skybuilders' Mineral Sand

Singular: chunk of approved grade 4 skybuilders' bluespirit ore
Plural: chunks of approved grade 4 skybuilders' bluespirit ore
Description:
Not only is this rock imbued with a spirit, but that spirit is feeling particularly blue. Perhaps being smashed repeatedly with a chisel will cheer it up.

Used in level 80 crafting recipes.
Name: Approved Grade 4 Skybuilders' Bluespirit Ore

Description:
The word “log” fails to amply convey the undeniable majesty of this immaculate specimen. Unfortunately, there are no suitable substitutes, unless one is content to call it a “tree with all the sticky-outy bits cut off.”

Used in expert crafting recipes.
Name: Approved Grade 4 Artisanal Skybuilders' Log

Description:
Being rather small, it is unusual for raspberries to be handled individually rather than by weight. This may also be because fruiterers are keen to avoid counting anything other than coins.

Used in expert crafting recipes.
Name: Approved Grade 4 Artisanal Skybuilders' Raspberry

Description:
In this case, “artisanal” refers to the caiman itself rather than the person tasked with procuring it. This scalekin is particularly gifted in the art of nest building, or at least it was before being clobbered over the head and dragged off to the skybuilders.

Used in expert crafting recipes.
Name: Approved Grade 4 Artisanal Skybuilders' Caiman

Description:
As the skybuilders neglected to specify the exact type of cocoon they would like delivered, its contents remain unknown. It could be home to anything from a wamoura pupa to the larva of a parasitic wespe. Nothing good, in other words.

Used in expert crafting recipes.
Name: Approved Grade 4 Artisanal Skybuilders' Cocoon

Singular: clump of approved grade 4 artisanal skybuilders' barbgrass
Plural: clumps of approved grade 4 artisanal skybuilders' barbgrass
Description:
The countless tiny barbs at the tips of this hardy plant are believed to deter grazing beastkin. However, to counteract this, those creatures have developed an especially tough lining to the inside of their mouths, and could probably bite down on a handful of broken glass without so much as batting an eyelid.

Used in expert crafting recipes.
Name: Approved Grade 4 Artisanal Skybuilders' Barbgrass

Singular: chunk of approved grade 4 artisanal skybuilders' cloudstone
Plural: chunks of approved grade 4 artisanal skybuilders' cloudstone
Description:
According to certain scholars, the islands of the Sea of Clouds are kept suspended in the air by large amounts of cloudstone. It is therefore advised not to mine too much of this valuable resource as it may cause the island to plummet from the sky.

Used in expert crafting recipes.
Name: Approved Grade 4 Artisanal Skybuilders' Cloudstone

Singular: bottle of approved grade 4 artisanal skybuilders' spring water
Plural: bottles of approved grade 4 artisanal skybuilders' spring water
Description:
Spring water is said to result from a series of complex processes that unfold deep underground. But in a place like the Diadem, where the normal laws of nature appear to be ignored entirely, it is impossible to say exactly where this water comes from.

Used in expert crafting recipes.
Name: Approved Grade 4 Artisanal Skybuilders' Spring Water

Singular: approved grade 4 artisanal skybuilders' ice stalagmite
Plural: approved grade 4 artisanal skybuilders' ice stalagmites
Description:
Be sure to hold this the right way up or it could be mistaken for a stalactite.

Used in expert crafting recipes.
Name: Approved Grade 4 Artisanal Skybuilders' Ice Stalagmite

Singular: sack of approved grade 4 artisanal skybuilders' silex
Plural: sacks of approved grade 4 artisanal skybuilders' silex
Description:
Similar─though rather less artisanal─sacks of silex are sold to the participants in Ul'dah's Coliseum. A well-aimed handful of the stuff can temporarily blind the opponent, though it is only a matter of time until these customers realize that the same is true of the sand that lines the arena floor, which is available for free.

Used in expert crafting recipes.
Name: Approved Grade 4 Artisanal Skybuilders' Silex
